Here are some common Docker commands for various tasks:

1. Basic Docker Commands:
Check Docker Version

bash
Copy
Edit
docker --version
List Docker Containers (running)

bash
Copy
Edit
docker ps
List All Containers (including stopped)

bash
Copy
Edit
docker ps -a
List Docker Images

bash
Copy
Edit
docker images
Pull an Image from Docker Hub

bash
Copy
Edit
docker pull <image_name>
Build an Image from Dockerfile

bash
Copy
Edit
docker build -t <image_name> .
Run a Container

bash
Copy
Edit
docker run -d --name <container_name> <image_name>
2. Container Management:
Start a Stopped Container

bash
Copy
Edit
docker start <container_name_or_id>
Stop a Running Container

bash
Copy
Edit
docker stop <container_name_or_id>
Restart a Container

bash
Copy
Edit
docker restart <container_name_or_id>
Remove a Container

bash
Copy
Edit
docker rm <container_name_or_id>
Remove an Image

bash
Copy
Edit
docker rmi <image_name_or_id>
3. Inspect and Logs:
View Container Logs

bash
Copy
Edit
docker logs <container_name_or_id>
Inspect a Container

bash
Copy
Edit
docker inspect <container_name_or_id>
Inspect an Image

bash
Copy
Edit
docker inspect <image_name_or_id>
4. Other Useful Commands:
Execute Command in a Running Container

bash
Copy
Edit
docker exec -it <container_name_or_id> <command>
Remove Stopped Containers

bash
Copy
Edit
docker container prune
Remove Unused Images, Containers, Volumes, Networks

bash
Copy
Edit
docker system prune
View Docker System Information

bash
Copy
Edit
docker info
These commands cover the basics, but Docker offers a lot more functionality, depending on your needs. Let me know if you need more specific details!
